[normal]We estimate that the majority of our customers who are not deemed as vulnerable will be paid their benefits directly under the new Universal Credit arrangements, which will include the housing element which is for their rent. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The concerns around housing costs being included in Universal Credit payments 
[normal]are well documented. Tenants who are subject to sanction will lose all their bene
[normal]fits and risk losing their home whereas those being sanctioned currently 
[normal]do not lose Housing Benefit.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]What [bold]impact [bold]do [bold]we[bold] [bold]anticipate over[bold] the coming months for [bold]our customers[bold]?[bold] [bold]&#xa0;[bold]In our area the private rented sector is limited and 
[normal]insecure, so the opportunities for people to downsize into this sector are both severely limited and undesirable. 
[normal]Research in this area shows for the area that Aragon operates in (
[normal]Central  B
[normal]edfordshire), 
[normal]the average private rent for a two
[normal] bedroom property is £156.13 per week, which is £29.18 per week above the Local Housing Allowance for the majority of the region. This means that should our tenants move to such properties, they face an average 18.6% shortfall, 
[normal]despite
[normal] occupying properties of the correct size. This means both a larger shortfall for tenants and higher Housing Benefit awards; the result is that costs are both higher for tenants and Local Authorities. Therefore, moving to the private rented sector is simply not a viable option in our region.
[normal]  The same is true for those living in South Northants Homes
[normal]’
[normal] area.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Furthermore, 
[normal]as a G
[normal]roup 
[normal]we 
[normal]do not have enough smaller units to rehouse all of those affected by the 
[normal]under-occupancy charge
[normal], so over time, we anticipate that our most vulnerable tenants will no longer have the capacity to maintain their tenancies, leading to evictions, increased levels of personal debt and the resulting pressures on public/private services, such as 
[normal]food banks
[normal], clothing banks, 
[normal]GUHG’s 
[normal]and the Council
[normal]s’
[normal] support teams and statutory services such as social services.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The councils
[normal]’
[normal] DHP budget
[normal]s will soon be spent, and 
[normal]our tenants currently maintaining their tenancies in this way will need to find another option.  There are limited options to move and as such, we anticipate that these families will quickly get into serious debt, both housing and otherwise
[normal] resulting in
[normal] a catastrophic impact on some households. The DHP scheme merely offers temp
[normal]orary respite from benefit cuts
[normal] 
[normal]and is
[normal] potentially pejorative, conditional, subjective and can become int
[normal]rusive.  In one instance our 
[normal]local authority r
[normal]efused
[normal] a DHP claim because the 
[normal]applicant paid 
[normal]for dental insurance
[normal].  T
[normal]he tenant in question has very bad teeth as a result of a medical condition.  Another DHP was refused for 
[normal]a wheelchair user, seeking work, t
[normal]hey were relying on 
[normal]broadband in order to do this but it was deemed that broadband was an unnecessary ‘luxury’. The overall effect on our tenants could be that they become demonised and treated less favourably for attempting to improve their quality of life. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We anticipate that it is the most vulnerable groups, such as homeless households and households with a 
[normal]disability who
[normal] will suffer the most.  Disabled households are the most difficult to transfer as the options open to them that are open to other tenants, su
[normal]ch as returning to work or the occasional
[normal] opportunity to downsize
[normal] are more limited.  They will often 
[normal]have no option but to find
[normal] the shortfall or face eviction. 
[normal]T
[normal]he total cost to the pub
[normal]l
[normal]ic purse, sh
[normal]ould they be evicted, 
[normal]is believed to be in the region of £7,000. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Those who have never had to manage their own housing costs will need a significant amount of support to build up the skills required to cope with UC, and if they fail to do so, which we unfortunately believe that some will, they too face the prospect of losing their tenancies
